value.0: "Now, is there anything I can help you with?"
"May the Nine Gods protect and inspire you."
"I will answer what I can. What topic would you like to speak on?"
"Good enough. Was there anything else?"
"Speak to Rafael. He runs the Temple Store. Anything else?"
"I would be pleased to offer you my services. I merely ask for a small donation to the temple. 20 gold will cure you of all woes."
"Very well. Anything else?"

value.0: "May Pharos judge you well."
"As a member of the guild, I will heal you for free."
"I love most of the people of the keep as my own children, though there are a few exceptions. What do you want to know?"
"There must be something very powerful forcing them out of the deep and making them band together. Ogres certainly are too weak of mind to organize an army like that."
"Whatever has subdued these creature's natural warring instincts must be stopped. There are many enemies left in those caves."
"I would suggest the Silver Lily, here in the north keep. It costs a little more than The Mossy Tree, but Garrot runs a good, clean inn. The Mossy Tree is more adventure than rest."
"I would suggest you speak to Rafael. He runs the Temple Store. There are also a number of other merchants here in the keep. Look around and I am sure you will find them."
"The Stan runs the Trades Guild. You can find him in his shop, The Trades, or in the Trades Guild Office, in the Guildhall."
"An important topic at this time, particularly for you. Enivid and Sir Becket have the advantage over you. What would you like to know?"
"She is an experienced warrior, and a paladin in the service of Jaess. She would be a good leader, though there are many who do not appreciate her righteous attitude."
"I think, given time and experience, she will grow to understand diplomacy a little better. As a follower of Jaess, she will serve her people as best she can. Anything else?"
"He is a loathsome man; a corrupt noble who would sell his own children to be slaves, if there was some gain in it. There is nothing else to say about him."
"Right now we are voting for Enivid. That could change, but I doubt it."
"You want me to change my vote? And who do you propose I change my vote to?"
"I see... that is an interesting suggestion."
"None of us here at the temple are willing to support you. I doubt I would be willing to change my mind. I suppose you could speak to the other priests though. Anything else?"
"The other two priests seem to think that you would make a good leader. If you did not care for our community at all, I guess you would not have tried so hard."
"I guess the temple could support your leadership, if you would make me a promise."
"That is the best answer you could have given. I guess maybe you do have some intelligence, maybe even some integrity (dare I hope?). Very well, the church will support your cause."
"I want you to promise that if something were to happen to the community that threatened the temple, you would protect our interests above the community's."
"What kind of leader has such disdain for <his/her> people that they would say such a thing? I will never vote for you. Enivid shall be our leader. Leave this holy place!"
"Since only one of my fellow priests agrees that you would make a good leader, I do not think I can vote for you. I am sorry. Was there anything else?"
"I would definitely vote for you, if you were a member of the Priest's Guild. Would you, as a priest of <CUSTOM6004>, like to join our guild?"
"I would definitely vote for you, if you were a member of the Priest's Guild."
"I would need to know which of the Nine Gods you follow first."
"Im glad you are pleased. Anything else?"
"We will be voting for you, of course."
"Now that the election has taken place, the importance of that subject has withered. Let us discuss something else."
"Very well, have you had enough time to consider your own faith? Are you willing to tell me who you follow?"
"Although it is my favorite topic, we have already had discourse on it. Let us talk about something else."
"That is not a good thing to lie about, <FirstName>. I suppose everyone makes mistakes though. Which God do you truly follow?"
"Are you interested in joining our guild now?"
"Ah yes, you return." Dynschall looks up as you approach, nodding in your direction. He seems genuinely happy to see you.
"How can I be of assistance, <FirstName>?"
"My Lord <FirstName>, it is an honor that you should come and visit our humble temple. How can I assist you now?"
"Welcome, <Brother/Sister> <FirstName>, Cleric of <CUSTOM6004>. How can I assist you today?"
"There have been no donations to <CUSTOM6004> at this time."
"There have been a couple of donations. Here is your share."
"Are you ready for your final task, <FirstName>?"
"Very well. Return when you are ready."
"You distributed the food then, <FirstName>?"
"Well, don't let the food go bad. The fish is salted, but still, the poor are hungry."
"I am pleased and you have done well. Though it was not a hard task, some might have been tempted to force the poor to pay for their food..."
"Your second test is your test of devotion. You must swear to all of the Nine Gods that you will uphold their faith and the faith of the community in all things."
"Once you have sworn, you will be a full member of the temple."

Cast visual effect on PC, something purple to show the vow was valid to the PC's god, but not the others.

value.0: "The gods find your vow unacceptable. Now swear truthfully and properly or leave this holy place!"
"Then be gone from this place, foul deceiver! I will look on you no more!"

value.0: "Some of the Gods find your vow acceptable, but others do not. Will you make the full vow and be welcomed here by all, or will you stand by the partial vow you have made?"
<StartAction>[Sigh]</Start> "Very well. You are now a member of the mysteries of the Temple of the Nine Gods."
"The gods find your vow acceptable. Welcome to the mysteries of the sacred Temple of the Nine Gods!"
"As a member of the guild, you will have the full support of our guild in your struggle to gain the throne. With you as the Lord of the keep, the church will be an effective power in the community."
"Good luck, <Brother/Sister> <FirstName>! May the gods go with you."
"Did you think that delivering the food was really the test? I had someone watching the beggars and I know you charged them for the food they were supposed to be freely given."
"You are much like Veragok, Patron of Thieves, and he might be pleased with the way you conducted yourself, but that does not mean I have to allow you into our temple."
"I can no longer stand to see you here. Leave this building!"
Dynschall glares at you, then turns his head and ignores you completely.
"So, young Dylan claims you are a hero, but young men often make snap judgments, without the benefit of the wisdom of age to guide them."
"Unless I am wrong, and I am rarely wrong, you are a warrior of some skill. Being a priest of Pharos, God of War, Lord of Battles, and the Supreme Judge, I have respect for your calling."
"When we met earlier I was still distracted by the death of my old friend, the Banner. I would love to discuss religion with you; or are you here about the election?"
"I find a lot can be told about an individual by a <man/woman>'s faith. So, which of the nine gods do you follow?"
Dynschall frowns at you and raises an eyebrow. "Do you not wish to tell me, or do you not follow any god?"
"Of course, I hoped for better, but expected nothing less from a druid. Should you ever seek to worship the creators, rather than the creation, I would speak to you about it."
"The immortal soul of every person in this community is my concern, thank you very much! Should you ever realize that and wish to speak of it, I will be here."

"A private faith, to precious to share with others is rarely a strong faith. If do not allow our faith to be tested, it cannot grow. But it is your choice. Should you ever wish to talk about it, I will be here."
"It is a sad and lonely path you walk, and one which is not well accepted within our community. If you ever seek the solace of a higher power, please come and speak to me about it."
"The Nine Gods are the balance and the sum. Each follows a different view of life, or alignment. Many break these into three categories, the Pantheon of Good, Evil and Neutrality."
"That is the balance, but it is a simplification, which is why we also call them the sum."
"All the gods together are more important than a single god. That is the only way that we can share a temple and get along, is through belief in the sum."

"If Suhili kept creating, and Mistress Death stopped destroying, what do you think would happen? All men and women would keep having children, but none would die, and eventually we would run out of room."
"Each god has a purpose, and because of that, even if I dislike the tenets of your faith, I still recognize you have a purpose in life."

Dynschall eyes you carefully. "That is exactly how I used to feel. Maybe I am just jaded, but I would suggest you hold those beliefs to yourself. You will have a difficult time getting along with others in this region."
"Still, I appreciate your love of good. It is good to see someone with a little righteous fervor."
"There are many who would think so, but the other priests and I agree that this philosophy helps to knit our community together, as much as anything can."
"Religion is very important to most of the people in our society. The few folk who do not have some faith usually feel very separate from the group."
"It does, though it really goes against my beliefs as a younger man. At one point in time, I would have tried to kill a thief as soon as I had evidence of <his/her> activities."
"I guess age has softened me... though if I caught one stealing from the temple... nothing would hold me back."
"Pharos is the God of Judgment, Lord of Battles, the Warrior. Mistress Death is the only god who did not spring from the eternal parents. She exists and has always existed."
"Callahi is the God of Commerce, the Wanderer, the Morning Star."
"Callahi is the God of Commerce, a greedy god, but also the god of diplomacy and travel. Some of the city-states in the south call him Silvertongue."
"His followers are bards, thieves, merchants, politicians and anyone traveling. He is the most powerful of the lesser gods, largely because his church is so wealthy."
"Few merchants would be so foolhardy as to enter into large negotiations without a hefty donation to Callahi's shrine."
"She is one of the most powerful gods and her true followers are among the most powerful priests in the known world. Despite this, she has few followers."
"Her demands on her clergy are strict and they lose themselves to her service. They own nothing for themselves and must follow the dictates of the church above their own interests."
"But everyone pays tribute to her, in hopes of good treatment in the afterlife. We all pay her some lip service, but she is not loved, except by a strange few, including our own Lavos."
"She is very powerful, perhaps the most powerful priest in the known lands. Despite this, she lives a very simple life, eschewing anything that does not come with her station."
"I would suggest you speak to her, though be wary. She seems to have taken an unnatural fascination in you. I tried to get her to tell me about it, but she does not... like me very much."
"Pharos the Warrior is the just god. He knows your purpose, your worthiness and when invoked, he judges whether your claim to victory is valid."

"The Banner was a follower of Pharos and in his last battle, Pharos decided to claim his follower and brought him into the otherworld. His claim to victory was just and so we won, despite our leader's death."
"Most of his followers are warriors, paladins, monks, and those who love justice. Those who carefully deliberate and then support a just cause are his champions."
"Churl is the Goddess of Destruction, Lady Chaos, the Storm. Rictos is the God of Magic, the Dominator, Lord of Power, The Mountain."
"Veragok is the God of Darkness, Patron of Thieves, Lord of the Outcasts, the Shadow."
"Veragok, known to the clergy of Pharos as the coward, is the forgotten child. The weakling who hides in the shadows and welcomes the outcasts of society into his dark and corrupt world."
"Those whose interests are only of themselves, thieves and assassins, beggars and burglars are the patrons of Veragok."
"Those who fear thieves will sometimes give tribute to turn the god's attention from their enterprises. Pharos has no patience for his brother's plots and petty jealousies."
"Veragok. Yes, Trip knows something of this god! I give him presents, little gifts and he welcomes me in the fraternity of outcasts. He is the caring god."
"You think he cares for you, but he only cares if you bring him gifts. He cares only for himself!"
Trip hisses and backs away from the priest. "I shall refrain from commenting in this conversation again. This priest preaches tolerance, but his words are no more than that."
"My appologies, Trip is it? Old hatreds die hard. But I should finish speaking to <FirstName>."

"Rictos, The Mountain, is the opposite of Churl, and hates her as much as he does his father, Jaess. He spawns the magic that steals from all the other gods. He values knowledge and careful planning."
"His followers include those who lust for power, be they mages, generals, emperors, or common street thugs. He loves a good conspiracy and those who would crush the meek into the earth."
"Pharos and Rictos have warred since the beginning. Rictos gains power, but loses it, because of his need to crush those weaker than him."
"Most feared of all the gods, when Churl looks upon you, it is a terrible thing to behold. Her eyes are lightning, her voice thunder, and even her followers fear her presence."
"Her followers include pirates and sailors, barbarians, evil druids, and those who enjoy dangerous lifestyles or cruel whims."
"Every time someone does something cruel or mean-spirited; every time a pure heart is tempted into evil, Churl grows in strength."
Dynschall's face seems to bleed with rage. "Pharos and Churl are destined to meet in combat, and his judgment shall destroy her. He is war for a purpose. She is meaningless, chaotic destruction."
"To compare the two is blasphemy. Do so at peril of your own life. Neither Pharos, nor Churl would be pleased with such a comparison."
Dynschall grits his teeth and spits on the floor. "You insult me and my god. If you want the church as your enemy, that is a good way to go about it!"
His red face calms at your words. "I believe you didn't. Such words are... hard to hear, but to an outsider I can see how the mistake could be made."
"Oh, <FirstName>, you do know how to offend a priest, don't you! Ha, ha!"
"Suhili, the Great Mother, the sun, shines upon us. Jaess is the Father-God, also known as the Divine Servant, the moon. Tamose is the spoiled child, the Hermaphrodite, the dawn and the dusk."
"Of course. Can you tell me whom you follow, or do you have more questions yet?"
"I shall struggle to maintain an open mind no matter whom you follow, though it might go against my very nature."
"I shall struggle to maintain an open mind no matter whom you follow, though it might go against my very nature."
Dynschall nods. "Well then, feel free to visit your god's shrine."
Dynschall frowns and obviously struggles to control his reaction. "Well then, feel free to visit your god's shrine."
A thoughtful look crosses Dynschall's face and he nods. "Well met then. Though I am not of your faith, I think there is room for you within our organization."

"We have never had a priest to your god here in the temple, but if you are interested in joining us, you have to pass a test. Joining the temple will give you access to donations, and make you a member of our guild."
"That is... disappointing. Should you ever change your mind, feel free to ask me about it."
"Then you shall be set two tasks. They are relatively easy, but will prove your dedication to the community, above your own self-interests."

"The first task is to distribute this food to the local beggars. There are three that spend most of their time in the central market. Return when you have completed this task and I shall set you the second."
"Best of luck, <FirstName>."
Dynschall nods politely. "You will definitely be wanting to speak with Rafael then. He is always interested in fleecing... I mean meeting another worshiper."
Dynschall frowns a little. "That is unfortunate. Rafael will not be pleased to meet another priest of his order, since he is much like his god, and rather jealously guards his position and wealth."
"Still, Callahi brings gold to the temple, which is always useful. Would you be interested in joining our guild?"
Dynschall nods politely. "You will definitely be wanting to speak with Lavos then. No wonder she has taken such an interest in you."
Dynschall frowns a little. "That is good. Lavos will be pleased to meet another priest of her order. With all of the dangers that have befallen our community lately, there has been much death."
"Would you be interested in joining our guild?"
Dynschall smiles. "It is good to meet a fellow worshipper of Pharos. I trust that you will hold true to our tenants, <brother/sister>."
Dynschall frowns a little. "This is a good day then, indeed. I have longed for several years to find and train a replacement who could bring honor to Pharos."
"The years have taken their toll on both my body and my soul. If you are interested in joining our guild, I would stay long enough to help you fit into the community before I retire."
"Would you take this responsibility willingly? Are you interested in joining our guild?"
"Which pantheon would you like to know more about?"
"Tamose, the perpetual, hermaphroditic child, who is beautiful to behold, but capricious in favors. The Child is the Dawning of every new day and also the Dusk, or end of every life."

"The Child's followers include lovers, bards, builders (for Tamose loves new things), smiths and sorcerers. If Tamose smiles upon you, then you shall be richly blessed, but his attention wanders easily."
"A follower of Tamose gains strength through manipulation of events and people. As a priest of Pharos, I see the destruction inherent in the Child's whims, though his heart and intent are pure."
"The Father-God, the Moon, the Mage, the Divine Servant... he is an enigma to me. Though he was the father of the other gods, he wants his followers to serve the good of all."
"Followers of the Moon include white mages, guardians, servants, monks, paladins and those few politicians who are not corrupt. Enivid is a paladin and follower Jaess."
"Jaess loves those who do good deeds, but do not claim them for glory. It is an attitude that I know is good, but I could never follow it. It is too humble a road."
"She smiles down upon us; allowing things to grow, inspiring birth and imbuing her followers with good health. When she sees evil, she burns it with her sharpest gaze."
"Followers of the Sun include farmers, peasants, midwives, rangers, paladins and occasionally a druid. Her followers gain strength through creation and loving acts of kindness."
"If you would know more about Suhili, you should visit her shrine or read some of the tombs in our library."
"Unless I am wrong, and I am rarely wrong, you are a warrior of faith. Being a priest of Pharos, God of War, Lord of Battles, and the Supreme Judge, I welcome you as a worthy comrade."

"Unless I am wrong, and I am rarely wrong, you are a warrior of faith; a monk. Being a priest of Pharos, God of War, Lord of Battles, and the Supreme Judge, I hope to welcome you as a worthy comrade."
"Unless I am wrong, and I am rarely wrong, you are a child of nature. Being a priest of Pharos, God of War, Lord of Battles, and the Supreme Judge, I hope to welcome you as a child of faith."
"Unless I am wrong, and I am rarely wrong, you are a dabbler in the arcane arts. Being a priest of Pharos, God of War, Lord of Battles, and the Supreme Judge, I welcome you as a potential ally."
"Unless I am wrong, and I am rarely wrong, you are of questionable character; perhaps a bard."
"Being a priest of Pharos, God of War, Lord of Battles, and the Supreme Judge, I warn you not to practice your charms or roguish abilities on my people."
"Unless I am wrong, and I am rarely wrong, you are of questionable character; a rogue."
"Being a priest of Pharos, God of War, Lord of Battles, and the Supreme Judge, I warn you not to practice your thieving abilities on my people."
"Unless I am wrong, and I am rarely wrong, you are a person of faith. Being a priest of Pharos, God of War, Lord of Battles, and the Supreme Judge, I hope to welcome you as a fellow disciple."
"Tell me, as a priest, which of the Nine Gods do you serve? There are three priests here in the temple. The other two are Lavos, servant of Mistress Death, and Rafael, a follower of Callahi."
"A fellow worshipper is always welcome, but the prospect of having the representative of another faith join us is... interesting."
"The gods wait for no <man/woman>, <Lord/Lady> <LastName>. I recommend you do what needs doing while there's still time."
"No, thank you."
"I have other questions for you."
"That is all."
"Do you sell supplies?"
"Where can I get healing?"
"Never mind."
"Of course."
